==Visual elements==
[[image:Nine Inch Nails Moline 08.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A Nine Inch Nails performance during the Live: With Teeth tour featuring the "teeth" lighting fixtures.]]
Since 1999, the visual design of Nine Inch Nails live shows have been created by [[Rob Sheridan]].  Nine Inch Nails shows typically feature a large amount of [[strobe light]]s,<ref name="unogateway">{{cite news
| url = http://media.www.unogateway.com/media/storage/paper968/news/2006/02/21/ArtsLeisure/Nine-Inch.Nails.Pummels.Fans.In.Lincoln-2550095.shtml
| title = Nine Inch Nails pummels fans in Lincoln
| author = Josh Bashara
| work = The Gateway
| date = [[2006-02-21]]
| accessdate = 2008-02-19}}</ref> projected images, and other visual elements.

[[Bill Viola]] designed a large triptych display for the Fragility tour.<ref name="Gergiev" />  The images displayed on the triptych focused on storm and water imagery.  The DVD release of ''And All That Could Have Been'', a tour documentary of the Fragility tour, features an audio commentary track by Viola describing the display and his inspirations for it.<ref name="AATCHB DVD review" />

Roy Bennett and Martin Phillips were responsible for the lighting design and stage design, respectively, of the Live: With Teeth tour.<ref name="WT lighting">{{cite journal
  | title = Production Profile: Nine Inch Nails
  | publisher = ''Projection, Lights and Staging News''
  | last = Steve 
  | first = Jennings 
  | date = [[2005-12-08]]}}</ref>  Bennett explained in a 2005 interview that the much of the lighting was done using a series of [[Light-emitting diode|LED lights]] arranged in "stalactites or stalagmites [formations] to tie in to the album artwork."  Also used were [[DLP]] projectors displayed on a gauze screen in front of the stage.  Using the gauze projection-screen, Phillip, Reznor, and Sheridan devised a "gag" where they projected "a sheet of glass shattering onto a downstage kabuki scrim that would drop as the glass shatters fell.  ... We settled on Trent swinging his guitar at the gauze [and] shattering it, but with all the pieces falling up as the [screen] flew out."<ref name="WT lighting" />  This particular trick can be seen in the tour documentary ''Beside You in Time''.

In contrast to the lighting of the Live: With Teeth tour, Performance 2007 featured minimalist lighting that shadowed Reznor.<ref>{{cite news
| url = http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,21692704-5003421,00.html
| title = Reznor `nails' it
| author = Jason Nahrung
| work = [[News Limited]]
| date = [[2007-05-07]]
| accessdate = 2008-02-19
}}</ref>

While many of the band's songs often generate [[mosh]] pits,<ref>{{cite news
| url = http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2000/06/09/DD87142.DTL&hw=Neva+Chonin&sn=076&sc=467
| title = Reznor Vents His Rage
| author = Neva Chonin
| work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]
| date = [[2000-06-09]]
| accessdate = 2008-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D48D3A80043D&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D
| title = Hammering point home Nine Inch Nails constructs great set from heat, crowding
| author = Tom Maurstad
| work = [[Dallas Morning News]]
| date = [[1994-05-05]]
| accessdate = 2008-02-19
| format = fee required
| quote = Unlike other shows where some stage-front area becomes the mosh pit, at Nine Inch Nails, the whole floor was a mosh pit.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF8FB704C264BC&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D
